In the Hobbesian conception, it’s anarchy that occasioned humanity to surrender certain sovereignties to a body called the state. The police, therefore, is central to statecraft — to tame our wild impulses for anarchy.
And thus, to paraphrase Thomas Paine’s Common Sense, the police, like dress, is the badge of lost innocence. But that badge is no licence to transgress the boundaries of civility, decorum, or moral sensibilities of society. Nor should it trash the reciprocal doctrine of the social contract.
Horrific atrocities
Yet, today, police trigger sends chills down our spines. Their horrific atrocities meted out on the citizenry are well documented. The public’s attitude towards the police is not fantasy. It’s informed by daily tragic experiences.
Nothing forms attitudes better than experience. We must appreciate that attitudes are nuanced and complex psychological conceptions that take time to establish but also can’t be wished away at a whim.



